description: HISTORYMy great uncle first bought this car in 1971. He was LAPD, and it hadbeen stolen off a used dealer's lot in Los Angeles, and he bought it as aninsurance recovery, when they found it without the engine. He bought a usedengine and transmission and had it installed. The parties that had stolen it,removed the exterior badges, removed all VINs, except for the stamp in the metalof the front trunk(pic 2) and painted over the original green, to a dark blue.This must have been a bad problem, because I even have a police trainingbulletin (pic 3, blue bulletin with VW outline) which the San Fran police deptput out to help ID VINs of stolen porsches and vw's. He liked the darkblue, so when the paint peeled in later years, he painted it over it again withthe same dark blue. The car lived in a garage in Burbank most of it's earlylife. But then when they moved to Palm Springs, it sat under a tree for a littlewhile. I heard about the car's new resting place, and talked him intoletting it come to me in 2004. He told me the engine had a bad "knocking", andthat it would need to be fixed.I received the car in 2004, 2 days before mytwins were born. The car got pushed into my garage, and I thought I would domore work on it. I removed the engine and started the tear down, When idiscovered it was beyond my abilities, I took it to a mechanic who told me theengine would cost an extraordinary amount to repair, more than I could afford soI again mothballed the project.In 2012 I trailored the car to a mechanic whoreplaced the front pan and did work on the front suspension, as this seems to bea bad area of rust for these cars.Then in 2013 I trailored it to Ralph'sAuto in Baltimore, where I traded my old engine for a 1968 engine. Ralph'smechanic did the instal, but did not do a total rebuild.

description: this is a 1970 Porsche 911T Targa VIN # 9110111018 this was literally a barnfind that i pulled out of a barn in Tennessee fortunately the rats didn'tget to it the owner moved to florida and left the car at his brother'splace in TN and did not drive the car for 7 years. it had been 2 years since hestarted it. he never drove the car much. the owner before him also didn'tdrive the car much. he told me he believes it to have 101k original miles thetub is very solid. the whole floor pan is rust free. there is a drain for thea/c that looks like rust but it is not. it has surface rust but is solid. thewhole car is rust free except a spot on the rear bumper which as shown in pic.there is surface rust here and there, especially up in the front sparecompartment, but i scraped it with a wire brush and the metal is solid all theway through. a good cleaning and POR15 would take care of it. the gas tank alsohas the coating peeling off, and it looks like it's really rusted, butit's all solid. the car had some later flares added to the rear quarters.they were very well done and look factory. obviously the mirrors are from alater car also. the paint really needs a buff. it looks better in the pics thanin real life. maybe even a wet sand. one front fender was done just to see whatwould happen and it actually came out pretty good. car has really good gaps.door shut with that familiar thud and don't hang or sag. the interior is inpretty good shape. the dash has a couple cracks. the seats are in good shape.the carpet shows wear and could use replacement if you chose to. but it isusable as is. there is an aftermarket a/c unit up front. there is no compressorso it will not work. best to look at the pics and see for yourself. the motor isa little bit of a mystery. the engine

description: The car has been sitting for a long time in a heated garage and will require atotal restoration. It is a whole car though, the glass is all in tact and notcracked. The sheet metal is solid at the rockers and jack post areas. It willneed floor pan work behind passenger seat area as there is a hole through to theground behind the driver seat. It is not shown from the interior photos becauseof carpet in back floor area but you can see from the underneath photos.Thefront pans are not bad, you can see patches in photos but there are no holes inthe front pan areas. The rockers and jack post areas are more solid than Ioriginally thought, see photos for your own opinion. It will require somestructural remediation at the torsion bar areas. Doors are in nice shape forage, door striker areas are solid and door hinge areas are solid. The frontbonnet area is not bad on top and in battery area but underneath at tow hookwill need to be replaced. The fuchs wheels are nice and original, the tires willhave to be replaced however the car rolls and can be moved easily. I don'tknow anything about the engine and/or transmission as the car has never beendriven in my ownership. The engine does not run and is frozen up, it does seemto have all the original injection system in tact. The engine number appears tobe correct for the period but I cannot attest that it is original to the car.The car has lots of potential for someone with experience.
